full_text:
@legrandmawak @desandro hello, 2.5 years in the future. They all divide into 16:9, standard widescreen:
16 * 20 = 320  ||  9 * 20 = 180
16 * 30 = 480  ||  9 * 30 = 270
16 * 40 = 640  ||  9 * 40 = 360

All factor nicely. Except SNES, and so the Mario World screenshot is in a different aspect ratio.
full_text(utf-8):

All factor nicely. Except SNES, and so the Mario World screenshot is in a different aspect ratio.'

full_text:
If being here causes you pain, remember: on Twitter, you are not a person. You are literally a brand.

You can't perform Conflict Resolution with Twitter. You can't set real boundaries. The people you talk to are not people either, not really.

Moments of humanity are incidental.

full_text:
Every time you're about to put effort into Twitter, just remember: "this is labor I am doing for free." 

And ask if it's worth it.

full_text: @TafferKing451 @DaveOshry How can we watch the teaser post-stream?
full_text(utf-8): b'@TafferKing451 @DaveOshry How can we watch the teaser post-stream?'

b'@playmadness @DanFloydPlus There are *reasons* it's being occluded: pulling the camera back or drastically changing the character's height would both have other substantial ramifications.

But that doesn't mean the "cinder block" effect isn't there.

And I have a feeling there are doable ways around it'

b"@playmadness @DanFloydPlus You don't need to be able to jump around like a ninja.

I literally didn't suggest changing the functionality of character movement at all.

I just want to feel my feet and legs hit the ground. Foot placement is a big part of the 'feel' of walking, and it's being occluded."

b"@DanFloydPlus Resident Evil 4.

Love that game, but It feels like my feet are cinder blocks.

Any over-the-shoulder 3rd person shooter that doesn't let me see enough of my legs (ideally my feet) -- so also The Last of Us 1 kinda (TLoU2 lets you zoom out a bit)."

b"@DanFloydPlus 2D Sonic games. 

So much time to slow down and speed up, but it's kinda fine cuz managing your momentum is half the challenge.

King's Field/Shadow Tower (Souls precursors) and pretty much every other retro, 3D dungeon crawler."

A). Present the game's core mechanics, staggered with space to experiment and get comfortable.

2/7

Perhaps worth clarifying: I'm not saying complex AI with intricate path finding and varied behaviors is *bad* in 2D action-adventures (<3 Rain World).

But I am saying it's not *necessary.* Sometimes the loop of just skirting and hitting obstacles is equally satisfying.

Popular indie game with a polished approach to the same ideas...

full_text:
Trying to program my first video game and absolutely failing to accomplish any of the lofty, dreamy ideas I had in my head has finally given me an appreciation for retro games.

It's so elegant: 
Enemies as moving obstacles. You're here; get there.

full_text:
I think the game might benefit from including a bit more depth to master in its movement mechanics, but we're splitting hairs a bit.

#AShortHike is a leisurely game done right. It contains a myriad of problems which are Just Easy Enough to solve.

kinda like a real hike.

13/13

full_text:
#AShortHike could have been a Walking Simulator. 

It could have said "the game is pretty and simple, a leisurely experience" but played like Dear Esther, just holding a key and changing one's x, y, and z coordinates. 

But it's not! 

12/13

full_text:
I find that many self-described "leisurely" games do not ask enough cognition of their players to be engaging and that understanding the role challenge plays in helping us enjoy leisure can help.

For example, the pejoratively named "Walking Simulators."

11/13

full_text:
That feels like an important distinction.

The threshold between Too Easy, Just Easy Enough, and Hard are unique to each player, but I think there's enough overlap that we can design intentionally for Leisurely vs Hard games.

10/13

full_text:
judging climbing distances, gaining momentum, competing with ai characters in simple challenges. 

The game never surpasses my skill with its mechanics, but it is consistently asking me to solve new problems.

That is not "really easy," it's Just Easy Enough.

And...

9/13

full_text:
To put it another way:

Fun Hard Game: each new challenge must be just above the comfortable limits of your capabilities

Fun Leisurely Game: each new challenge must be *just* below the limits of your capabilities.

I find #AShortHike leisurely

8/13
full_text(utf-8):

8/13'

full_text:
HERE'S THE POINT

If a hard game offers pleasure by building stress toward eventual release,

A leisurely game offers pleasure as a consistent stream of content that asks Just Enough cognition to require your attention, but never more than you are prepared to give.

7/13

A leisurely game offers pleasure as a consistent stream of content that asks Just Enough cognition to require your attention, but never more than you are prepared to give.

7/13"

full_text:
That's the key of engagement in a game, requiring cognition, mental 'exercise.'

A "tough-as-nails" game contains stressful cognition. frustration. The fun is not the failures, but the exponential satisfaction of overcoming what seemed 'too difficult.'

So: what is leisure?

6/13

There is plenty on top, pretty sea shores, funny dialogue, etc. but, at its most basic, you: Run, Jump, Glide, and Climb. 

Games are verbs, and in #AShortHike those are your verbs. It must make traversal engaging to succeed.

To prove that, let's imagine the game but BAD

full_text:
#AShortHike may a tad avant garde. It sells its mini open world as a relaxing stroll 

Stereotypical games (plenty of exceptions) are flashy and intense, but A Short Hike is not so fundamentally different

It fits neatly among 3D platformers. So, it is about fun movement

3/13

full_text:
Leisure implies not only a lack of stress but also "pleasure."

Too easy can be 'boring,' and forcing yourself through something boring is not pleasant.

To be "pleasant" something must be low-stress but still 'engaging.'

"Engaging" is too broad. Let's narrow it down

2/13

full_text:
So last thing and then... /thread

I am enjoying having more followers, and I appreciate it if you all are actually interested in what I have to say.

But let's be weary of becoming social media positivity sponges looking for scraps of social capital.
full_text(utf-8):
b"So last thing and then... /thread

I am enjoying having more followers, and I appreciate it if you all are actually interested in what I have to say.

But let's be weary of becoming social media positivity sponges looking for scraps of social capital."

full_text:
So maybe #NoComradesUnder1k isn't pointless, but we do need to seriously consider the systemic point of the platform we're using. What are the bounds of that?

That's for our own wellbeing if nothing else. Getting a shitload of retweets on a random tweet was legit stressful.
full_text(utf-8): b"So maybe #NoComradesUnder1k isn't pointless, but we do need to seriously consider the systemic point of the platform we're using. What are the bounds of that?\n\nThat's for our own wellbeing if nothing else. Getting a shitload of retweets on a random tweet was legit stressful."

full_text:
But I'm not open-and-shit on this opinion. I've been pretty careful about who I follow back (I will not be offended if you stop following me 'cuz I didn't reciprocate), trying to make a few actual friendships out of this.

And my world does feel a little bigger...
full_text(utf-8): b"But I'm not open-and-shit on this opinion. I've been pretty careful about who I follow back (I will not be offended if you stop following me 'cuz I didn't reciprocate), trying to make a few actual friendships out of this.\n\nAnd my world does feel a little bigger..."

full_text:
It's not like people with 1000 followers are "the bourgeoisie" or some other ridiculous, literal analog.

But, I dunno, it doesn't seem like getting an influx of Twitter followers based on one presumed political similarity is really a big solidarity spreading tool either...
full_text(utf-8): b'It\'s not like people with 1000 followers are "the bourgeoisie" or some other ridiculous, literal analog.\n\nBut, I dunno, it doesn\'t seem like getting an influx of Twitter followers based on one presumed political similarity is really a big solidarity spreading tool either...'

full_text:
So I can't help but feel like #NoComradesUnder1k - which again, I have enjoyed a lot!! - is less a leftist insurgence onto a platform and more just a social capital raffle.

That's probably sounding harsher than I meant it too, but I hope you can see what I'm getting at...
full_text(utf-8): b"So I can't help but feel like #NoComradesUnder1k - which again, I have enjoyed a lot!! - is less a leftist insurgence onto a platform and more just a social capital raffle.\n\nThat's probably sounding harsher than I meant it too, but I hope you can see what I'm getting at..."

full_text:
the result isn't loads of opportunities for organization or helpful insights, it's droves of left-ey branded social media positivity (negative takes about the Right count as positivity from this perspective too).

And that's not 'bad', but it's also not new
full_text(utf-8): b"the result isn't loads of opportunities for organization or helpful insights, it's droves of left-ey branded social media positivity (negative takes about the Right count as positivity from this perspective too).\n\nAnd that's not 'bad', but it's also not new"

full_text:
I get the impression most of the people who "succeeded" just had a random tweet asking for followers go small-viral (happened to me overnight), or spam followed a lotta people they don't know.

And Twitter's not a platform for organizing, it's for protracted engagement, so...

full_text:
And I'm just so glad - and shocked - that a game so superficially mechanically "bland" as #KentuckyRouteZero totally gets that.

It's so subtle I couldn't tell you whether it was an intention or an instinct, but it makes me so goddamn happy.

Love you, @cardboardcompy !!
full_text(utf-8):
b'And I'm just so glad - and shocked - that a game so superficially mechanically "bland" as #KentuckyRouteZero totally gets that.

It's so subtle I couldn't tell you whether it was an intention or an instinct, but it makes me so goddamn happy.

Love you, @cardboardcompy !!'

full_text:
Whole new style of traversal, whole new camera, whole new atmosphere.

That's some shit I've been saying for years: mechanics define your game's atmosphere at *least* as much as the aesthetic (graphics, sound, etc.)

Seriously, I feel like I can't overstate this.
full_text(utf-8):
b"Whole new style of traversal, whole new camera, whole new atmosphere.

That's some shit I've been saying for years: mechanics define your game's atmosphere at *least* as much as the aesthetic (graphics, sound, etc.)

Seriously, I feel like I can't overstate this."

full_text: And after 4 whole chapters of this mucky soup, I was kinda worried, like "hey, uhh, this seems a bit monotone to build to any sort of climax" and then they pull not only a total visual shift (which wouldn't be enough), but a mechanical one! Last thing I expected.
full_text(utf-8): b'And after 4 whole chapters of this mucky soup, I was kinda worried, like "hey, uhh, this seems a bit monotone to build to any sort of climax" and then they pull not only a total visual shift (which wouldn\'t be enough), but a mechanical one! Last thing I expected.'

full_text:
But! #KentuckyRouteZero finds little interactive ways to pull you into its languid, midwestern depression vibe. 

Driving "puzzles" are always just vague enough to be worrisome, but easy enough you don't get lost and rare enough the novelty never wears off.
full_text(utf-8): b'But! #KentuckyRouteZero finds little interactive ways to pull you into its languid, midwestern depression vibe. \n\nDriving "puzzles" are always just vague enough to be worrisome, but easy enough you don\'t get lost and rare enough the novelty never wears off.'

full_text: *almost always. The Xanadu thing went on a bit too long, and some of the vignettes on the boat had a bit too much dead air, but I suppose you can't please everyone - particularly not if we have ADHD and suck at reading.
full_text(utf-8): b"*almost always. The Xanadu thing went on a bit too long, and some of the vignettes on the boat had a bit too much dead air, but I suppose you can't please everyone - particularly not if we have ADHD and suck at reading."

full_text:
I have more to say though. 

#KentuckyRouteZero is, by some accounts, a slog. Click there, read text. Minimal animation. 

But in my playing I've found that it always walks *righttt* up to the edge of "boring" but always manages to toss in a nice mechanical wrinkle just in time
